@Ticki I'd like to argue your point from another angle: If you have a slow-ish but secure hash by default, you only need a profiler to find out those usages that are your bottleneck and optimize those (perhaps even by just using fewer hash lookups, or parallelizing the hash computations and computing hashes up-front, ...). There are always multiple ways to do this, but measuring performance is the comparatively easy first step. Once you're done, your code runs reasonably fast and is mostly secure.

On the other hand, let's say we have a blazingly fast but somewhat insecure hash function. Your program will run faster by default, :star2: :cake: :100:! However, it will unexpectedly run _much_ slower on some workloads (either the :star: stars aligned :moon: so that you get a pathological-case workload or some clever colleague has studied his hash books and found you one) – to the point of grinding to a halt :hand: and eating your CPUs like it's going out of style. Debugging these problems is much harder than just running a profiler, and even with the aforementioned colleague, you're likely to miss some instance of the problem.

That's why having a secure hash function by default makes sense, even if it's slower for most workloads.

@briansmith cause SipHash-1-3 is already secure enough for any usage in hash table.
More over, it is still not broken for any other usage, so at this moment of time, it is still cryptographically secure.
It is better to use "faster implementation of SipHash-1-3", than "faster implementation of SipHash-2-4".
